Kafka has BUILT-IN stream processing — no external framework needed:

<pre><code>// Kafka Streams — Java library for real-time transformations
StreamsBuilder builder = new StreamsBuilder();
KStream&lt;String, DeliveryEvent&gt; events = builder.stream("delivery-events");

// Real-time aggregation: deliveries completed per hour per warehouse
KTable&lt;Windowed&lt;String&gt;, Long&gt; completedPerHour = events
    .filter((key, event) -> "COMPLETED".equals(event.getStatus()))
    .groupBy((key, event) -> event.getWarehouseId())
    .windowedBy(TimeWindows.ofSizeWithNoGrace(Duration.ofHours(1)))
    .count();

completedPerHour.toStream().to("warehouse-metrics");

// ksqlDB — SQL-like syntax for streaming
// CREATE STREAM delivery_stream (deliveryId VARCHAR, status VARCHAR, ...)
//   WITH (KAFKA_TOPIC='delivery-events', VALUE_FORMAT='JSON');
// SELECT warehouseId, COUNT(*) FROM delivery_stream
//   WHERE status = 'COMPLETED'
//   WINDOW TUMBLING (SIZE 1 HOUR)
//   GROUP BY warehouseId EMIT CHANGES;</code></pre>

<strong>REWE use cases:</strong>
• Real-time dashboard: deliveries per hour per warehouse
• ETA recalculation: stream of driver positions → join with route data → updated ETA
• Alert: if delivery not completed within expected window → notify operations

Every partition has ONE leader replica and N-1 follower replicas (replication factor N). All produce and consume requests go through the leader — followers only replicate.

<pre><code>// Topic with replication factor 3:
// Partition 0: Leader=Broker1, Followers=Broker2,Broker3
// Partition 1: Leader=Broker2, Followers=Broker1,Broker3
// Partition 2: Leader=Broker3, Followers=Broker1,Broker2

// If Broker1 dies:
// Partition 0: new Leader elected from ISR (Broker2 or Broker3)
// Partition 1 & 2: unaffected (leader is on other brokers)</code></pre>

<strong>Key insight:</strong> Kafka distributes leaders across brokers for load balancing. Each broker is leader for some partitions and follower for others.

A follower is "in-sync" if it has replicated all messages within <code>replica.lag.time.max.ms</code> (default 10s). Only ISR members can become leader.

<pre><code>// ISR = [Broker1(leader), Broker2, Broker3]  ← all caught up
// Broker3 goes slow (network issue)...
// After 10s: ISR = [Broker1(leader), Broker2]  ← Broker3 removed
// Broker3 catches up again...
// ISR = [Broker1(leader), Broker2, Broker3]  ← Broker3 rejoins

// WHY IT MATTERS:
// min.insync.replicas=2 means:
// Producer with acks=all will FAIL if ISR < 2
// This prevents writing to a single replica (risk of data loss)</code></pre>

<strong>Interview connection:</strong> "How does Kafka guarantee no data loss?" → acks=all + min.insync.replicas=2 + replication.factor=3. This ensures at least 2 replicas confirm before producer gets success.

ONE broker in the cluster is elected as Controller (via ZooKeeper/KRaft). It handles:

• <strong>Leader election:</strong> When a broker dies, controller picks new leaders for its partitions from ISR
• <strong>Broker membership:</strong> Detects join/leave via ephemeral nodes
• <strong>Partition reassignment:</strong> Distributes replicas across brokers

<pre><code>// Scenario: Broker 2 dies (was leader for partition 3)
// Controller detects (ZooKeeper ephemeral node disappears)
// Controller picks next replica in ISR as new leader
// Controller sends LeaderAndISR request to all affected brokers
// New leader starts serving produce/consume requests
// Followers start replicating from new leader

// All this happens in milliseconds — clients see brief timeout
// then reconnect to new leader automatically</code></pre>

<strong>KRaft mode (Kafka 3.3+):</strong> Replaces ZooKeeper with internal Raft consensus. Same concepts, simpler deployment.

Each partition is a directory on disk containing <strong>segments</strong>:

<pre><code>// /kafka-data/delivery-events-0/   ← partition 0
//   00000000000000000000.log         ← segment (messages)
//   00000000000000000000.index       ← offset → position mapping
//   00000000000000000000.timeindex   ← timestamp → offset mapping
//   00000000000005238476.log         ← next segment (after roll)
//   00000000000005238476.index

// Segment rolls when:
// - Size exceeds log.segment.bytes (default 1GB)
// - Time exceeds log.roll.ms

// Retention:
// log.retention.hours=168 (7 days default)
// log.retention.bytes=-1 (unlimited)
// Old segments are DELETED (or compacted)</code></pre>

<strong>Why segments matter:</strong>
• Sequential writes only (append to active segment) → fast
• Old data deleted by removing entire segment files → efficient
• Index allows O(1) offset lookup within segment
